  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's a real, tangible barrier that shows up in the shop floor and the classroom alike. As a mechanic who's worked on cars and engines for over forty years, I've seen how people hesitate to tackle complex problems when they fear being labeled 'not smart enough.' Back in my day, we didn't have the term 'stereotype threat,' but I've noticed how students from underrepresented groups often freeze when they're in a room full of people who seem to know everything. It's like when you're at the mechanic's shop and you're nervous about fixing a car because you're worried someone will think you're not good at it. That same fear can hold back kids from pursuing STEM fields, even if they have the talent. The question isn't whether we should address it—it's how we can do so without making things worse. In Kansas City, where I live, we've got a lot of families who want their kids to have opportunities, but the system sometimes tells them they're not cut out for engineering or physics. I think the answer lies in creating safe spaces where everyone feels they belong, not in pushing people to conform to stereotypes. It's about showing up, listening, and helping kids see that their curiosity and hands-on skills matter just as much as any textbook knowledge. We need to stop treating STEM as a 'special' field for a select few and start building communities where everyone can thrive.",
